								<p>
								In 1915, the Chicago Chinese Christian Church (CUCC) was established at the Chinatown Center in Chicago. It has established the CUCC-North, CUCC-South, CUCC-West, and the Peide Community Center to serve Chinese people in Chinatown. <br>
								According to Father Annette Moy, of CUCC: <br>
								<i>“The church hosts different language activities on Sunday mornings, including an English-speaking event, two Cantonese-speaking events and a Mandarin-speaking event. Also, every Friday night, the church will host a number of youth activities, ranging from second-year to college students
 The church has been in the Chinatown community for many years. During these years, many changes have taken place. The church has changed from a small house to three buildings and is still developing.”</i>
								The church vision is to be a Great Commission Church that glorifies God by reaching out to Chinatown, Greater Chicago, and the world at large. To achieve this vision, these are the core values that will guide the church: A Commitment to Worship, A Commitment to Prayer, A Commitment to Biblical Teaching, A Commitment to Missions, A Commitment to Discipleship, A Commitment to Family Ministry, A Commitment to Multiculturalism, and A Commitment to Unity. </p>
